e United States while also showing how he was a major force in pushing Marxism beyond Europe—especially into the Arab world and other regions of the global South. Rather than taking one interpretive position on Gramsci, the contributors demonstrate the ongoing relevance of his ideas to revolutionary theory and praxis.Contributors. Alberto Burgio, Cesare Casarino, Maria Elisa Cevasco, Kate Crehan, Roberto M. Dainotto, Michael Denning, Harry Harootunian, Fredric Jameson, R. A. Judy, Patrizia Manduchi, Andrea Scapolo, Peter D. Thomas, Catherine Walsh, Pu Wang, Cosimo Zene  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCommunismzItalyxHistory. 0aMarxian historiography. 0aPhilosophy, Marxist. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aBurgio, Alberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasarino, Cesare, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCevasco, Maria Elisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrehan, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDainotto, Roberto M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDainotto, Roberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDenning, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarootunian, Harry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJameson, Fredric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJameson, Fredric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJudy, R. A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManduchi, Patrizia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScapolo, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1